    <fr:title text="Sufficient Statistics">Sufficient Statistics</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:meta name="author">false</fr:meta>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>A statistic <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T(X)]]></fr:tex> is sufficient for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\theta ]]></fr:tex> if the conditional distribution of the data <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> given <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T(X) = t]]></fr:tex> does not depend on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\theta ]]></fr:tex>. Intuitively: if someone hands you <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T(X)]]></fr:tex>, they could regenerate a fresh dataset with the same distribution without knowing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\theta ]]></fr:tex> — so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> lost nothing about <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\theta ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(60, 90, 180, 0.8);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(60, 90, 180, 0.05);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(60, 90, 180, 0.8);">Example.</html:span> 
<html:em>Bernoulli.</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {x}; \theta ) = \theta ^{\sum _{i} x_i}(1 - \theta )^{n - \sum _{i} x_i}]]></fr:tex>. The distribution only depends on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x}]]></fr:tex> through <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _{i} x_i]]></fr:tex>, so this is a sufficient statistic.
</html:div>
</fr:mainmatter>
